Keloid can be a serious issue. If your keloid is too raised please see a doctor.  I got a keloid on my helix 5 years after getting it pierced. I didn’t take my one seriously and kept applying tea tree oil but eventually my dad took me to see the doctor where we found out I need to get injected in my keloid to get rid off it. I have multiple piercings ( 4 earlobes on each ear, daith, tragus, rook, conch, 5 helix) from my experience tea tree oil helps, but the best thing to do from experience is to not touch,change or move your jewelry at all during the healing process. The best thing I've found to clean my new piercings with is salt water soaks.....that's it. I also use a travel pillow at night so I'm not putting pressure on my healing piercings. I use to get the bump all the time because I was twisting my new piercings or changing them before they were completely healed. Once I quit touching or moving them I didn't get a bump and the heal faster. I also quit using q-tips and just use paper towels.

The only thing I have to say about piercings is that when it comes to healing everyone is totally different. My piercings have healed amazingly with H2Ocean but I can see where the sea salt can be drying and delay the healing process. I have also used Provon and it’s incredible too. The next time I get pierced I’m definitely trying the NeilMed because I’ve always been curious about it but I’ve barely heard anyone talk about it. Keloids can’t be healed they have to be removed. An actual keloid is an overgrowth of scar tissue.  What you had is hypertrophic scaring. Those can be healed. That is not the same as a keloid although both look similar. What most people don’t think about is that surgical steel has nickel which most people are allergic to. So at first the jewelry can seem fine but once the ear starts to heal that’s when there is usually problems. Smart choice to change your jewelry. I have 2 tragus piercings, 1 conch, 1 rook, 1 daith, 7 lobes and a nose piercing. I don’t have a helix piercing yet because those are the hardest to heal and stay infected. I’ve had hypertrophic scaring on 6 of them. All of the ones that had surgical steel got irritated. They all went away though.

Kayla Young no bump piercing discs !

Kayla Young the key to getting rid of them is catching them when they first start developing. I usually suggest to my clients aggressively scrubbing them with saline on a q-tip. It’s a very backwards process but I’ve done this to all my clients and it’s always worked. They key is consistency, everyday 3 times a day until it’s gone, sometimes it will bleed and that’s fine. After the shower it’s easier because your skin is softer. WhT happens is it actually gets worse before it’s better and later by layer it gets smaller and flakes off. How long it takes depends on the severity you start with. But you can’t give up, the minute you decide to give it a break they can start again. If it’s uncomfortable when you’re scrubbing then you’re doing it correctly, sitting there petting it isn’t going to do anything. Check me out @ piercings_by_val. 😊

Tea tree oil might be too harsh for some, so another cheap and great remedy is sea salt water. Boil about half a cup of water and half a teaspoon of sea salt. Wet a napkin with the solution and let it sit on the bump for 15-30 minutes. You can do this 2 times a day. I got two bumps on my my tragus piercing one on the inside that went away in three days with the method mentioned above and the one on the outside which was much bigger went away in about a week.
